"**1. Highest‑Risk Areas (by cyclomatic complexity & impact)**  \n| File | Score | Why it’s risky | Immediate concern |\n|------|-------|----------------|--------------------|\n| **ApiError.js** | 18 | Custom error class with many branches; used everywhere | Propagates faulty errors to the client |\n| **asyncHandler.js** | 18 | Wrapper around every async route; any bug leaks stack traces | Uncontrolled promise rejection |\n| **course.controller.js** | 17 | 140 + lines, many nested callbacks | High chance of logic errors & duplication |\n| **user.controller.js** | 15 | Similar to course controller | Same risk |\n| **user.model.js** | 16 | Complex schema with many virtuals & hooks | Data integrity risk |\n| **auth.middleware.js, lesson.model.js, section.model.js, course.model.js** | 14 | Repeated validation & business logic | Tight coupling |\n| **constant.js** | 8 | Centralized config, but mutated at runtime | Hard to audit |\n| **db.js** | 6 | Singleton connection pattern; no graceful shutdown | Resource leak |\n\n---\n\n**2. Suggested Refactoring Order**  \n\n1. **Core Error & Async Layer**  \n   * `asyncHandler.js` → switch to a proven library (e.g., `express-async-handler`).  \n   * `ApiError.js` → simplify to a plain error type; add `statusCode` & `payload` only.\n\n2. **Controllers**  \n   * Extract business logic from `course.controller.js` & `user.controller.js` into **Service** classes (`CourseService`, `UserService`).  \n   * Keep controllers thin – validate input, call services, return responses.\n\n3. **Models & Middleware**  \n   * Refactor `user.model.js`, `course.model.js`, `lesson.model.js`, `section.model.js` into modular schemas with clear virtuals / hooks.  \n   * Move validation logic from models into **DTO**/validation middleware (Joi, Yup).\n\n4. **Auth & Routing**  \n   * Refactor `auth.middleware.js` into a reusable JWT/Passport strategy.  \n   * Split `course.route.js`, `user.route.js` into route modules that only bind endpoints to controller actions.\n\n5. **Configuration & DB**  \n   * Replace `constant.js` with a proper config package (`dotenv`, `config`).  \n   * Rework `db.js` to use an async init/close cycle and support connection pooling.\n\n6. **Testing & CI**  \n   * Add unit tests for services and models before integrating back into the API.  \n   * Set up linting (ESLint), formatting (Prettier), and CI pipeline.\n\n---\n\n**3. Architecture Issues**\n\n* **Monolithic Express Stack** – All business logic lives in controllers; no separation of concerns.  \n* **Duplication & Tight Coupling** – Re‑used validation & error handling scattered across files.  \n* **No DTO/Validation Layer** – Raw request data is passed straight to services/models.  \n* **Global Config Mutation** – `constant.js` changes at runtime, making debugging hard.  \n* **Poor Error Propagation** – Custom `ApiError` is complex; async handler may swallow errors.  \n* **Resource Leak Risk** – DB connection is a singleton with no graceful shutdown.  \n* **Missing Tests & CI** – Makes refactoring risky.\n\n---\n\n**4. Actionable Improvements (one‑sentence each)**  \n\n1. **Replace custom async wrapper** with `express-async-handler`.  \n2. **Simplify ApiError** to just `status` & `message`.  \n3. **Create Service layer** (e.g., `CourseService`) to hold business logic.  \n4. **Introduce DTO/validation** middleware (Joi) for every endpoint.  \n5. **Extract config** to environment‑based modules (dotenv + config).  \n6. **Implement graceful DB shutdown** (`process.on('SIGTERM')`).  \n7. **Add unit tests** for each service and model.  \n8. **Set up ESLint + Prettier** to enforce style & catch bugs early.  \n9. **Document the API** (OpenAPI/Swagger) to clarify contracts.  \n10. **Move to TypeScript** (optional) for type safety across the stack.  \n\nFollow the refactoring order above; test each step thoroughly before moving to the next to keep the application stable."